root.pub-comments: “While there is ample evidence that Tokalau Fijian and Polynesian form a subgroup, the immediate relationships of the rest of Fiji are far from clear” (Geraghty 1983:389).

child.pub-comments: “Thus it is claimed that Tokalau Fijian, although it clearly subgroups now with other Fijian languages (that is, shares most innovations), originally subgrouped with Polynesian” (Geraghty 1983:381).
Geraghty notes that there are very close ties between Southeast and Northeast Viti Levu, which he calls Eastern Viti Levu (Geraghty 1983:330).

child.publications: Geraghty, Paul. 1983. The History of the Fijian Languages, 483. Honolulu: University of Hawaii Press.

child.pub-comments: Southeast Viti Levu “is a clearly definable group internally, but differs from Kadavu in that it shares numerous features with other groups, particularly Northeast Viti Levu, Nadrau and Tokaimalo showing a very close relationship” (Geraghty 1983:317-18). Also, “a large body of lexical items is shared exclusively by three communalects—Namosi, Waidina, and Lutu—which occupy a relatively isolated area in the mountains of Southeast Viti Levu” (Geraghty 1983:319).

child.pub-comments: Geraghty notes that the Northeast Viti Levu communalects “are relatively conservative...and have not innovated a great deal, but have changed largely by borrowing lexicon from neighbors” and “that this borrowing, too, has probably been in small doses, except that recent Standard Fijian influence has been felt strongly, especially in Lovoni and Namena” (Geraghty 1983:320).

child.pub-comments: Geraghty states that there is support for a larger group that includes the whole Vanua Levu, even Southeast Vanua Levu, which is that there are two forms that are shared by “all and only the Vanua Levu communalects”, which are takari “door” and vua- “grandchild” (1983:337).

“The Southeast Vanua Levu languages—Navatu (C), Tunuloa, and Naweni—show very little cohesion as a group, but share a few features with both Northeast Vanua Letu and Lau. I suspect, however, that my sample is not a good one. The Navatu people are immigrants, and the language of Naweni appears to have undergone heavy Standard Fijian/Colloquial Fijian influence in recent times. Tunuloa may, therefore, be the only bona fide Southeast Vanua Levu language in our sample, and it is unfortunate that the data from Tunuloa are not as extensive as those for most other communalects” (Geraghty 1983:328).

child.pub-comments: Node not named by author. “Over a greater distance, a larger number of innovations are shared by Western, Central, and Northeast Vanua Levu” (Geraghty 1983:330).

“Lying between two fairly well-defined groups—Northeast and West Vanua Levu—Central Vanua Levu...is poorly defined, and shares features East and West as much as it shows them internally” (Geraghty 1983:324).

“Within the Central Vanua Levu languages, there appears to be a north-south division. South Central (Nabelebale and Savusavu) shows vulaci 'morning'...and the distinctive marker bā” (Geraghty 1983:325).

child.geography: spoken in all of Bā province (except for the village of Navai, near Nadarivatu); all of the Nadrogā-Navosā province (except for the villages Nadrau, Nabouwaqa, Nagā (alias Vanualevu), Rewasau, and Naqelewai); all of the Sērau province (except for the Deuba area, by Navua on the coast, comprising the villages of Sadrō and Sauniviuto, the island of Yanuca, and the Namosi-speaking village of Nukusere on the Navua river); a portion of western Namosi province, containing the villages of Wainimākutu, Navuadrā, Nadolī, Korovou, Wainilotulevu, Naiyalayala, and Nasoqo; and, a portion of western Naitāsiri province, containing the villages of Nasauvere, Nasava, Matawailevu, Narokorokoyawa, Korovou, and part of Sawanikula
